{
  "id": "hungarian-basics",
  "title": "Hungarian Language Basics",
  "subtitle": "An introduction to one of Europe's most unique languages",
  "difficulty": 1,
  "readTime": "12 min",
  "tags": [
    "languages",
    "Hungarian",
    "linguistics"
  ],
  "state": {},
  "content": {
    "type": "Fragment",
    "children": [
      {
        "type": "Section",
        "props": {
          "title": "1. Why Hungarian is Special"
        },
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "Callout",
            "props": {
              "type": "info"
            },
            "children": "Hungarian (magyar) is spoken by ~13 million people and is one of the few non-Indo-European languages in Europe."
          },
          {
            "type": "p",
            "children": "Hungarian stands out for three key reasons:"
          },
          {
            "type": "ComparisonTable",
            "props": {
              "headers": ["Feature", "What It Means"],
              "rows": [
                ["Finno-Ugric Origin", "Related to Finnish and Estonian, NOT to neighboring Slavic or Germanic languages"],
                ["Agglutinative", "Words are built by stacking suffixes (one word can be a whole sentence!)"],
                ["Vowel Harmony", "Suffixes change their vowels to match the root word"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "DeepDive",
            "props": {
              "title": "The Finno-Ugric Mystery"
            },
            "children": "How did a Uralic language end up in Central Europe? The Magyar tribes migrated from the Ural Mountains region around 895 AD, settling in the Carpathian Basin. Despite 1000+ years surrounded by Indo-European languages, Hungarian kept its unique structure."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "Section",
        "props": {
          "title": "2. Alphabet & Pronunciation"
        },
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "Callout",
            "props": {
              "type": "warning"
            },
            "children": "Hungarian has 44 letters! This includes 14 vowels and unique digraphs (two-letter combinations that represent single sounds)."
          },
          {
            "type": "p",
            "children": "Key pronunciation rules:"
          },
          {
            "type": "ComparisonTable",
            "props": {
              "headers": ["Letter", "Sound", "Example"],
              "rows": [
                ["sz", "s (as in 'sun')", "szép (beautiful)"],
                ["s", "sh (as in 'ship')", "só (salt)"],
                ["cs", "ch (as in 'church')", "csók (kiss)"],
                ["gy", "soft 'dj' sound", "nagy (big)"],
                ["ny", "ñ (as in Spanish 'niño')", "nyár (summer)"],
                ["zs", "zh (as in 'measure')", "zseb (pocket)"],
                ["ly", "y (as in 'yes')", "lyuk (hole)"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "DeepDive",
            "props": {
              "title": "Vowel Length Matters!"
            },
            "children": "The accent mark (´) indicates a LONG vowel, not stress. This changes meaning! Compare: kor (age) vs kór (disease), hal (fish) vs hál (sleeps over). Always pronounce accented vowels longer."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "Section",
        "props": {
          "title": "3. Vowel Harmony"
        },
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "p",
            "children": "Hungarian vowels are divided into two groups that don't like to mix:"
          },
          {
            "type": "ComparisonTable",
            "props": {
              "headers": ["Back Vowels", "Front Vowels"],
              "rows": [
                ["a, á", "e, é"],
                ["o, ó", "ö, ő"],
                ["u, ú", "ü, ű"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "Callout",
            "props": {
              "type": "info"
            },
            "children": "Rule: Suffixes must match the vowel type of the root word!"
          },
          {
            "type": "p",
            "children": "Examples with the suffix 'in' (-ban/-ben):"
          },
          {
            "type": "ComparisonTable",
            "props": {
              "headers": ["Word", "Vowel Type", "With Suffix"],
              "rows": [
                ["ház (house)", "Back (á)", "házban (in the house)"],
                ["kert (garden)", "Front (e)", "kertben (in the garden)"],
                ["könyv (book)", "Front (ö)", "könyvben (in the book)"]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "Section",
        "props": {
          "title": "4. Essential Phrases"
        },
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "ComparisonTable",
            "props": {
              "headers": ["Hungarian", "English", "Pronunciation"],
              "rows": [
                ["Szia!", "Hi! / Bye!", "SEE-yah"],
                ["Jó napot!", "Good day!", "YOH NAH-pot"],
                ["Igen", "Yes", "EE-gen"],
                ["Nem", "No", "nem"],
                ["Köszönöm", "Thank you", "KØ-sø-nøm"],
                ["Kérem", "Please / You're welcome", "KAY-rem"],
                ["Elnézést", "Excuse me", "EL-nay-zaysht"],
                ["Beszél angolul?", "Do you speak English?", "BEH-sayl AHN-go-lool"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "Callout",
            "props": {
              "type": "info"
            },
            "children": "Notice 'angolul' ends in -ul? That's the 'in [language]' suffix, following back vowel harmony with angol (English)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "Section",
        "props": {
          "title": "5. Agglutination in Action"
        },
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "p",
            "children": "Watch how a single Hungarian word can express what English needs multiple words for:"
          },
          {
            "type": "ComparisonTable",
            "props": {
              "headers": ["Hungarian", "Breakdown", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["ház", "ház", "house"],
                ["házam", "ház + am (my)", "my house"],
                ["házban", "ház + ban (in)", "in the house"],
                ["házamban", "ház + am + ban", "in my house"],
                ["házaimban", "ház + aim + ban", "in my houses"],
                ["házaitokban", "ház + ai + tok + ban", "in your (plural) houses"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "DeepDive",
            "props": {
              "title": "The Famous Long Word"
            },
            "children": "Megszentségteleníthetetlenségeskedéseitekért means 'for your (plural) repeated pretending to be unable to be desecrated.' It's 44 letters—one for each letter in the alphabet! While artificial, it shows the language's agglutinative power."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "Section",
        "props": {
          "title": "6. Numbers 1-10"
        },
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "ComparisonTable",
            "props": {
              "headers": ["Number", "Hungarian", "Pronunciation"],
              "rows": [
                ["1", "egy", "edj"],
                ["2", "kettő", "KET-tø"],
                ["3", "három", "HAH-rohm"],
                ["4", "négy", "naydj"],
                ["5", "öt", "øt"],
                ["6", "hat", "hot"],
                ["7", "hét", "hayt"],
                ["8", "nyolc", "nyolts"],
                ["9", "kilenc", "KEE-lents"],
                ["10", "tíz", "teez"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "Callout",
            "props": {
              "type": "info"
            },
            "children": "Fun fact: Hungarian uses 'kettő' for standalone '2' but 'két' before nouns (két alma = two apples)."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
